вЉў obs-self-ref-easy
  given В§p5-self-describing
  yield observations

  вЉў= observations в†ђ "SELF-REFERENCE IS EASY: В§ makes it trivial. The program reads its own source as a string. No paradox, no fixpoint, no infinite regress. This is because В§ is STATIC вЂ” it gives the parse-tree, not the execution state. The hard self-reference (reading your own output before you produce it) is impossible in Cell by design. Immutability prevents it."

вЉў obs-linear-boring
  given В§p5-self-describing
  yield observations

  вЉў= observations в†ђ "STRICTLY LINEAR: this program has zero parallelism. Each cell depends on the previous one. The dependency graph is a chain: selfв†’predictв†’verifyв†’reflect. This means Kahn's algorithm always picks exactly one cell. Confluence is trivially satisfied (only one execution order exists). To test confluence properly, need branching deps like p1."

вЉў obs-meta-vs-eval
  given В§p5-self-describing
  yield observations

  вЉў= observations в†ђ "В§ IS ANALYSIS, NOT EXECUTION: this program proved that Cell can DESCRIBE itself. But it cannot EXECUTE itself вЂ” that requires cell-zero's eval-one. В§ gives you the code as data. cell-zero gives you the ability to run code-as-data. The self-describing program is introspection; cell-zero is metacircular evaluation. Both use В§ but for fundamentally different purposes."

вЉў obs-prediction-verification
  given В§p5-self-describing
  yield observations

  вЉў= observations в†ђ "THE PREDICTION LOOP IS ELEGANT: self analyzes the program, predict computes the execution order, verify checks the prediction DURING execution, reflect synthesizes. This is a provably correct program вЂ” its output describes its own behavior, and the description can be verified. This pattern (analyze в†’ predict в†’ verify в†’ reflect) could be a standard Cell idiom for self-testing programs."
